\begin_layout Standard
This is an optional section which you can read for further understanding.
 In a nutshell, we are trying to access the on board GPIO(s) via the userspace
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://elinux.org/images/4/4f/02-linux-quick-start.pdf
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in Linux.
 To be more precise we are trying to use the sysfs
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
http://www.makelinux.net/books/lkd2/ch17lev1sec8
\end_layout

\end_inset

 interface.
 sysfs is a virtual filesystem which enumerates the devices and busses attached
 to the system(board in our case) into a file system hierarchy that can
 be accessed from userspace.
 It's generated by the kernel and always mounted at /sys.
 The GPIO sysfs interface allows users to manipulate any GPIO from userspace.
 Since it uses 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "gpiolib"
target "http://elk.informatik.fh-augsburg.de/rtlabor/gnublin-lpc3131/work_eplpc3131/Dokumente/005_gpio.pdf"

\end_inset

, it is able to dynamically utilize all GPIOs on the system.
 The preloaded Angstrom image on the MinnowBoard already has all the GPIO
 on J9 header exported to the userspace by default.
\end_layout

